threats.label: Vodafone - CTB Locker Encryption Ransomware
threats.executiveSummary: Imitating a Vodafone template, these Italian-language emails refer to an electronic invoice instructing the recipient to view the attachment. The attachment is a .zip archive containing an executable file representing the CTB Locker encryption ransomware that encrypts files on the victim machine and changes the desktop background to a payment data image. The payment locations for this malware are located on the Tor web and request payment in Bitcoins, making it impossible to track any payments.

threats.label: Undelivered Message - JSDropper, Locky
threats.executiveSummary: These multi-language subject lines claim to deliver a document needing to be viewed by the recipient. Attached to each message is a .zip archive containing a hostile JavaScript application used to download and run a sample of the Locky encryption ransomware. Once Locky is run on the victim's computer, the malware seeks out and encrypts a wide variety of files ranging from personal documents and images to mission-critical business files such as software source code and security certificates. At runtime, the malware relies on a set of command and control locations hard-coded into the binary to report the newly infected and encrypted computer. Although the ransomware was unable to encrypt the machine, when encrypted the victim is presented with a ransom note listing the Tor-hosted payment sites and instructions for accessing these locations where he or she can find the ransom terms, amounts, and instructions for obtaining and rendering the Bitcoin required for payment.
